Stroop: The Stroop Color and Word Test (SCWT) is a neuropsychological test extensively used to assess the ability to inhibit cognitive interference that occurs when the processing of a specific stimulus feature impedes the simultaneous processing of a second stimulus attribute, well-known as the Stroop Effect.

#baseline data 

cmpst_all %>%
  select(patient_id, visit, stroop_color, stroop_word, stroop_color_word) %>%
  filter(visit == "Baseline") %>%
  drop_na() %>%
  summarize(
    n(),
    mean_color = mean(stroop_color),
    sd_color = sd(stroop_color), 
    mean_word = mean(stroop_word),
    sd_word = sd(stroop_word),
    mean_colorword = mean(stroop_color_word),
    sd_colorword = sd(stroop_color_word)
  ) %>%
 knitr::kable()

HVLT: Hopkins Verbal Learning test, assess acquisition and delayed recall, detecting the earliest signs of dementia

#longitudinal plots
cmpst_hvlt <- select(cmpst_all, patient_id, gender, visit, hvlt_immed, hvlt_discrim) 

cmpst_hvlt %>%
  filter(patient_id == 4000) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=visit, y = hvlt_immed)) +
  geom_point() 
## Warning: Removed 4 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

#calculate the difference
cmpst_hvlt_immed <- cmpst_hvlt %>%
  select(patient_id, gender, visit, hvlt_immed) %>%
  drop_na() %>%
 pivot_wider(
  names_from = "visit",
  values_from = "hvlt_immed",
  ) %>%
  select(-Week24) %>%
  mutate(
    change = Week14 - Baseline
  )

PANAS: Positive & Negative Affect Scores can range from 10-50 for both the Positive and Negative Affect with the lower scores representing lower levels of Positive/Negative Affect and higher scores representing higher levels of Positive/Negative Affect. Participants utilizing PANAS use a 5-point scale in which they determine if a concept applies.

Montgomery-Åsberg Depression Rating Scale. This test is used by clinicians to assess the severity of depression among patients who have a diagnosis of depression. The MADRS includes 10 items and uses a 0 to 6 severity scale, scored following the interview. Higher scores indicate increasing depressive symptoms. Ratings can be added to form an overall score (range 0 to 50); no weights are used. Cut-off points include: 0 to 6 – symptom absent, 7 to 19 – mild depression, 30 to 34 – moderate, 35 to 60 – severe depression.
